description:
23 December 2012. Montecito, Santa Barbara County, California. The general consensus seems to be that this bird may not be identifiable or may be a hybrid Rose-breasted x Black-headed. Characters that are odd include the very buffy breast, mostly dark maxilla, and brown (rather than dark brown) auriculars and lateral crown stripes, but with black streaks going most of the way across the chest.

Notes from September 2017: I just went through a large series if specimens of Pheucticus grosbeaks and at present I think that this is a Rose-breasted Grosbeak. It could be a hybrid, but I'm not seeing many characters that couldn't also be within the range of variation of pure Rose-breasted. The streaking on the flanks and chest is far too thick for any Black-headed, and there is considerable variation in the extent of streaking on the center of the chest in Rose-breasted. Maxilla color is also variable in Rose-breasted, with some females showing some dark. When Rose-breasted shows buff on the chest it is concentrated on the upper chest as in this bird, whereas a Black-headed has the buff or orangish extending from the chest all the ways down to the lower flanks, often contrasting with some yellow on the center of the belly even in the dullest females. 
I would expect a hybrid to show thinner streaks, not just fewer streaks, though of course a hybrid can't be eliminated entirely.

I found this insect on 12/16/12. I found this insect at 32.792722,-117.121127. This moth was found near a very large tree in someones backyard. The moth very brave. It allowed to carry it for a few moments before flying off. No matter how close I got to it, it would fly away until it was in my hands. This picture was taken on 12/12/12.This insect was found in a front yard at 32.829206,-117.168506. The butterfly was pollinating flowers while I was observing it. The butterfly also seemed very afraid of human contact. Whenever I came too close to it, it would fly away. Though, when it flew away it always came back to the same spot. This observation is part of the High Tech High Insects of San Diego.

This picture was taken on 10/17/12.
This Fruit Fly was found in a house at 32.829206,-117.168506. I notice that it was very attracted to the scent of apples in the room. I also noticed that the fruit flies would only come out during the night time when there wasn't a lot of people around. So I devised an experiment with apple juice and soap mixed together. The fly was attracted to the sent of apples, and they were caught in the soap. I was able to take a picture of this fly after it died in the soap. This observation is part of the High Tech High Insects of San Diego Field Guide.

This picture was taken on 12/15/12. This drosophila melanogaster was found at 32.829206,-117.168506. The bee was found taking nectar from a flower. There must have been a hive near by because the bee was very aggressive, and a bit protective. While I was taking a picture of another insect the bee came to me, and it stung my hand. After it stung me I noticed that it slowly started to descend, and it's back started throbbing. It stood perfectly still and died. That is when I took a picture. This observation is part of the High Tech High Insects of San Diego Field Guide.

This insect was found at 32.812279, -117.234206. It looks as though it is Taeniothrips simplex. It was found in the corner of a room in an area that had previously been occupied by boxes. description: Would have liked to get a better photo of this, but natural light was crap. Very cool little anemone, though.

Ron Wolf found this one and we were all wondering what it might be. Similar to Hallaxa chani in shape, but the branchial plume is too spread out, and there's no purple in the plume or the rhinophores. Since at least a few of the tuburcles have dark pigmentation, I'm wondering if this might be an incredibly pale Doris montereyensis.
Not sure why the edges look green under the flash.

This tiny dorid is confusing me. ~5mm long, rhinophores seemed lamellate, tuburcles spiculate, body shape was an even oval with no noted enlargement on either end, foot did not seem to extend much beyond the mantle as in Akiodoris, but it did have a nice white trim. Found crawling on surfgrass in a pool pretty high on the reef. I'm assuming this is some kind of Adalaria, maybe Adalaria sp. 1 in Behrens, but not sure.
How do you distinguish E. indianorum and E. tinctum?
One of many. Must have seen at least 10 individuals, which is a lot for this species.
Note to self: Baptodoris is the one with oral tentacles. Oi.

description:
Ring necked ducks and Buffleheads are frequent winter visitors to Big Rock, but this year I've spotted a new migratory friend: a Common Goldeneye.

Far more skittish and shy than any of the other ducks here, the Goldeneye has been eluding me ever since I started spotting him out of the corner of my eye earlier this week. At first I thought he might've been an extra shy female bufflehead, due to the similar head markings, but yesterday we made eye contact and I got a view of the brilliant gold before he hurriedly paddled off around the corner of the building.

I snapped a few shots with my iPhone later in the afternoon when I spied him again near the bridge.
